1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:18,000
All right. I'm Emilye Crosby working with the Southern Oral History Program University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

3
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:23,000
And I'm here today conducting this oral history as part of the Civil Rights History Project,

4
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:29,000
which is an undertaking of Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of African American History and Culture

5
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:32,000
and the American Folklife Center in the Library of Congress.

6
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:40,000
This is June 25th, 2013, and we're here today with Mr. William Lucy at the Smithsonian offices

7
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:51,000
and the other people present at the interview are John Bishop, who's filming Elaine Nichols of the Smithsonian African American Museum and Charmin Townsend.

8
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:58,000
Mr. Lucy, would you be willing to tell me a little bit about your family and growing up?

9
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:00,000
I understand you were born in Memphis and moved to California.

10
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:09,000
Born in the city of Memphis, my father was from a Catherine, Alabama, my mother was from a Uniontown, Alabama.

11
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:15,000
I grew up in Memphis up until about the age of seven plus.

12
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:25,000
I moved to California in March of 1942 just after World War II started.

13
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:36,000
I actually grew up in Richmond, California from about seven plus years old until I left Richmond in 1966.

14
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:40,000
Was the 1966, is when you left Richmond?

15
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:41,000
Yes.

16
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:45,000
Was the war the reason that your family went from Memphis to California?

17
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:55,000
Yes. My father worked for Memphis Light, Gas and Water until the war started in December of 1941.

18
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:00,000
He, along with any number of folks, were recruited for the war effort.

19
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:08,000
They left from Memphis and went to the Bay Area and went to work for Kaiser shipyards.

20
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:11,000
Did they have any trouble leaving Memphis, do you know?

21
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:16,000
Not at all. At that time, the government was recruiting for the war effort.

22
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:20,000
Yeah. So, do you have any memories of Memphis from those early days?

23
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:29,000
Well, I went to elementary school and Memphis to about the fifth grade, I think it was fourth of fifth grade.

24
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:39,000
And Memphis was pretty typical of most cities in the south, segregated as it could get.

25
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:47,000
The political participation was under the thumb of a fellow by the name of Edward Hull "E.H." Crump.

26
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:57,000
My father received his job from Mr. Crump and worked for Memphis Light, Gas and Water until we left in 1941.

27
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:04,000
But mid-December, we left in about March in 1942.

28
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:10,000
So, after you moved to California, what was it like for you there?

29
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:16,000
Well, in the early years, it was a total war effort. Up until the war ended in about 1945.

30
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:25,000
I went to Memphis Elementary School and California and then went to junior high and high school in California.

31
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:28,000
And California was radically different than Memphis Tennessee.

32
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:32,000
Of course, I was young and didn't know the significance of the difference.

33
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:39,000
We all lived in a wartime house and projects.

34
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:52,000
Everybody lived together. Kaiser Shipyards had developed four shipyards in Memphis, I mean in Richmond proper.

35
00:03:52,000 --> 00:04:02,000
And virtually everybody in Richmond worked for either standard oil, Ford Motor Company, or work for Kaiser in the shipyards.

36
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:05,000
When you say we all lived together, that's the workers?

37
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:11,000
Workers, I mean there was tremendous amount of defense housing built for the war effort.

38
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:13,000
And is this integrated housing? It was in.

39
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:17,000
Okay. So, do you have good memories of those years?

40
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:24,000
A very good memories. Our schooling was good, segregated but good.

41
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:36,000
Through junior high school, it was a good environment. When the war ended, the assumption was that people would go back where they came from and turned out not to be quite true.

42
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:50,000
You had a number of people who went to different states but the bulk of the African American community remained in Richmond until it came a point in time to really remove the defense housing.

43
00:04:50,000 --> 00:05:02,000
But our early childhood was pretty good. The education system was radically different than Memphis Tennessee, both through junior high school and high school.

44
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:08,000
Were you aware of that at the time? I mean was it very noticeable to you as a child?

45
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:14,000
The only thing that was noticeable is that we didn't have a substantial number of white people there.

46
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:20,000
We had the Mexican Americans and African Americans all living in the same area.

47
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:25,000
Okay. So, after the war, did your father continue to work with Kaiser?

48
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:32,000
No. At the close of the war effort, he opened his own business. He was a mechanic.

49
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:42,000
I guess, self-taught. He worked on automobiles, trucks, heavy equipment, construction equipment. He did that for a number of years.

50
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:46,000
Can you describe your parents for us? Tell us about them a little?

51
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:54,000
I think there were typical people from the south, primarily from the rural south.

52
00:05:54,000 --> 00:06:02,000
My father, I'm not quite sure of the level of education that he achieved but he was fundamentally self-taught.

53
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:13,000
He worked, as I said, for Memphis Light, Gas and Water. And what was interesting, he was, I saw his work papers and he was described as an unskilled laborer.

54
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:20,000
Prior to the war effort, six weeks after he went to work for Kaiser, he was a journeyman welder.

55
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:28,000
And that's not true from that is when the government has a priority, it can be achieved, whatever they have to do to make it happen.

56
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:36,000
My mother was a seamstress for many years and then opened a restaurant.

57
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:40,000
I'm not quite sure of the years but she ran that for a number of some time.

58
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:51,000
Did you have brothers and sisters? One brother in my, Joe Lucy Jr. who was two years older than myself.

59
00:06:51,000 --> 00:07:01,000
And so after you, are there other significant memories that you have from your childhood, things that were important or formative for you?

60
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:09,000
Well, I mean we had a typical growing up experience as youngsters in junior high school and high school.

61
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:23,000
We did the sports thing, baseball, basketball, football. After graduation from high school, I attended El Cerrito High School as opposed to Richmond High School.

62
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:32,000
And our sort of growing up years was just like the thousands of other kids in the center of situation.

63
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:40,000
We all went to school together, we all played together, we all grew up together and many of us still maintain contact now.

64
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:45,000
And after you graduated from high school, you went to Berkeley?

65
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:52,000
I went to work first for the Mare Island Naval Shipyard and worked there for two years.

66
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:58,000
In 1953, I went to work for Contra Costa County, California in the engineering department.

67
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:07,000
And during the course of that work went to the University of California at Berkeley in the amateur of the research courses.

68
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:14,000
And I shouldn't say worked in that but studied that for a couple years at the same time working for the county.

69
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:19,000
Was that something where they would pay you to go to school or was something that you were interested in?

70
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:25,000
No, this was done to enhance my opportunity for promotion on my regular work schedule.

71
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:30,000
I worked at Contra Costa County, California in the materials and research laboratory.

72
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:42,000
And at that time this was a very new area of study for highway construction, roads, buildings, dams, bridges.

73
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:46,000
So what was your work at that time?

74
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:54,000
I was initially what's called an engineering aid which was the entry level position in the laboratory system.

75
00:08:54,000 --> 00:09:05,000
I worked at that for about three years then transferred to the same department to the survey and right away division.

76
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:14,000
I came back into the laboratory and ultimately worked 13 years for the county, all but one or two of them in the materials and research department.

77
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:22,000
When I left employment in the county, I was the system materials and research engineer for the county.

78
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:27,000
And how was the work you did then different than your entry level work?

79
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:43,000
Well, there was a series of positions in the laboratory involved both laboratory testing and there's basically quality control and design and materials for highway construction.

80
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:50,000
The entry level was basically taking samples and doing sort of the fundamental test activity.

81
00:09:50,000 --> 00:10:04,000
When I became a super what was called a supervised and material stester, I ran the laboratory with about seven or eight personnel under my supervision.

82
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:21,000
The series of civil engineers, the system civil engineers, junior civil engineers, all of them working on quality control tests for highway construction, water, asphalt, oils.

83
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:44,000
And in 1953, I believe when Federal-Aid Highway Act of 1956 under the system, states had to be responsible for the quality control of materials that would enter construction.

84
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:51,000
And counties assumed their responsibility of a farm to the freeway road development.

85
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:55,000
Could we take a little pause? Okay, we're back on.

86
00:10:55,000 --> 00:10:59,000
How did you get involved in working with the union?

87
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:06,000
While I was working at the county, I was invited to join the union.

88
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:11,000
So I joined what at that time was an employee association.

89
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:19,000
During the course of the association work, the issue became why are we not a union?

90
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:24,000
I mean, we were in a very heavily unionized county, a very heavily unionized state.

91
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:33,000
And we were a civil service organization and there were many of us who believed that the civil service system did not meet our needs.

92
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:45,000
Civil service in those days had gone far beyond its original mandate of testing for qualified employees to be submitted for hire.

93
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:52,000
Civil service systems had began to make decisions on wages, benefits, etc.

94
00:11:52,000 --> 00:12:02,000
Which I basically felt was an issue that should be decided upon by the employer and the employees in some sort of a formal bargaining process.

95
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:15,000
So we discussed and debated and put the issue to a sort of a year long forum on whether we should be a union or continue to be an association.

96
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:26,000
And the employees who were part of our membership voted to seek out the maze and means of becoming a legitimate union in the true sense.

97
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:34,000
We had that election, the pro union group won the election, we set out to become a true collective bargaining vehicle.

98
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:38,000
Sounds like you were pretty actively involved in that discussion?

99
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:46,000
Well, I'm sure there were others who were perhaps more active, but at least I put a good deal of time into the issue because I thought it was so basic.

100
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:53,000
Yeah. What were the things that struck you as most important at the time about being part of a union?

101
00:12:53,000 --> 00:13:00,000
Well, the process in the civil service system, which is a good system, was a good system in our county.

102
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:11,000
But the issue of wages, hours, and conditions of employment as an association civil servant, you could protest after something had happened to you.

103
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:15,000
You didn't have a whole lot of rights in that process.

104
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:24,000
We thought that there should be legitimate grievance procedures with the defined process for resolution of just day-to-day problems.

105
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:33,000
And we certainly felt that, in regard to wages and benefits, employees have a basic right to be a part of that discussion that determines that.

106
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:42,000
Do you have looking back where there are influences in your growing opera, your experiences that predisposed you to that?

107
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:50,000
Well, I was employed in the county. I met a number of people who were old trade unionists.

108
00:13:50,000 --> 00:14:01,000
I think probably the two that had the greatest impact and influence on myself was a fellow by the name of Ben Russell, who worked for the county government at that time in the civil service department.

109
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:22,000
Another fellow by the name of Red Ielo, who was a blacksmith, you could have a wider difference between the functions and both of them felt very strongly about the need to have a trade union, truly represented people in the true trade union system.

110
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:31,000
And I think Mr. Ielo probably had more to do with the formation of thought.

111
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:47,000
But the two of them had a tremendous influence on how I felt about our rights as employees to a process where we were recognized as participants in decisions that affected our work life.

112
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:52,000
And am I correct that you went from working for the county to working for the union?

113
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:53,000
Yes.

114
00:14:53,000 --> 00:15:00,000
So can you describe sort of how you made that evolution to actually become a full time employee for the union?

115
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:11,000
Well, our union after going through this year long discussion and debate about trade unionism versus association functions.

116
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:15,000
And I learned a lot and I think grew a lot.

117
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:31,000
And in the course of the union's action, a contest between who did we want to join since we had made the decision to be a union, what union and who.

118
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:39,000
And during those days, there were not many unions who thought that should be redactively in the public sector.

119
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:48,000
If you recall, President Franklin D. Roosevelt, when he passed the National Labor Relations Act, specifically excluded public employees.

120
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:55,000
And we used to make the case of what's the difference between a bus driver and the private sector who drives his bus, ten blocks.

121
00:15:55,000 --> 00:16:01,000
And then a public employee drives it another ten. They both do the same thing, requiring the same skills.

122
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:07,000
And they therefore have the same basic rights to wages and benefits.

123
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:14,000
And so we caught the attention of the American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees.

124
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:22,000
At that time, who was led by a fellow out of Wisconsin, Mr. Arnold S. Zander,

125
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:36,000
who had grown up in the public service. He was the president, but he was being challenged by a fellow out of New York by the name of Jerry Wurf.

126
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:42,000
We had a very clear vision of what workers in the public are private sector ought to be entitled to.

127
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:49,000
And so they saw what we were doing and what we were talking about.

128
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:59,000
And in 1964, in the contest for the leadership of the union, Mr. Wurf was successful.

129
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:05,000
So we replaced a pro civil service leader with a pro union leader.

130
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:14,000
And Mr. Wurf, in about a year or so, saw the worker that we were trying to do in the kinds of issues we were focusing on.

131
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:19,000
And asked if I'd be interested in coming to work for the National.

132
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:24,000
And I was a little reluctant because I had only been out of my zip code one time.

133
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:36,000
So we talked about it in the question of what can we do if we have the sort of pro worker sense about ourselves.

134
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:41,000
And the public sector, the collective bargaining was very, very new.

135
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:53,000
And it was my belief that if our union was able to impact on issues, both work issues and social issues,

136
00:17:53,000 --> 00:18:00,000
maybe a union as an institution could be a good vehicle for a social change.

137
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:06,000
So as a result of that thinking you went ahead and made the leap to spot your concerns?

138
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:18,000
Yes, I left the county service in about June of 1966 and came to work for the National.

139
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:23,000
As the Associate Director of the Department of Legislation and Community Affairs.

140
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:28,000
And so what you said that one of your hesitations is you'd only been out of your zip code one time.

141
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:32,000
Well, from Memphis to California.

142
00:18:32,000 --> 00:18:37,000
And what was the new job going to entail? Was it going to be relocating or travel?

143
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:41,000
Oh, it meant relocating from Richmond, California to Washington, D.C.

144
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:46,000
The scope of the work was very unclear.

145
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:57,000
What we did see, however, was the growing influence of the federal sector in the affairs of state and local government.

146
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:09,000
I don't mean negatively, but funding programs, rules and regulations that related to how things were to be done.

147
00:19:09,000 --> 00:19:14,000
In our union, we were growing union in the public sector.

148
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:25,000
We felt we had to have a presence in those discussions, whether it was social welfare or whether it was employment security,

149
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:32,000
that we had to have at least a voice in the process in order to be sure how it will affect our workers.

150
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:40,000
So during this same period, the Southern Civil Rights Movement is taking place.

151
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:47,000
So from probably when you're a what a young adult, into this transition to the National.

152
00:19:47,000 --> 00:19:50,000
So what was your awareness of that?

153
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:59,000
Well, if you live in the South, you're aware of civil rights, either presence or absence all the time.

154
00:19:59,000 --> 00:20:11,000
Much of our thought, synonym to areas, there was a great struggle among agricultural workers at that time, particularly farm workers.

155
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:23,000
Cesar Chavez, another fellow by the name of Larry Itliong was in the process of forming the United Farm Workers.

156
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:34,000
And they were engaged in a big struggle in Central California with the Gallo around the grape industry.

157
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:37,000
Later on, it went on to lettuce and other things.

158
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:41,000
Our union and many of our folks identified with that.

159
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:50,000
So we were quite aware of the power and the pressure that major agribusiness could put on workers.

160
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:58,000
Same in the civil rights struggle, the real issue of Southern Civil Rights fighting was really about economic exploitation.

161
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:02,000
The same as it was with the Mexican farm workers.

162
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:06,000
And so did you think about it through that time period?

163
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:10,000
We thought about it, but that was at that point a whole lot we could do.

164
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:25,000
I believe, like Dr. Martin Luther King Jr believed, that trade unions as an institution can have great impact on the processes that govern people's lives.

165
00:21:25,000 --> 00:21:31,000
But I didn't understand how those could be implemented.

166
00:21:31,000 --> 00:21:50,000
What probably had a major piece of it, major people influence, was when we took on the simple question of survivor benefits for descendants of Panama Canal construction workers.

167
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:58,000
The descendants were without any benefits whatsoever, even though our ships were sailing easily through the canal.

168
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:02,000
Just think about three hands full of these people left.

169
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:07,000
The government has a basic responsibility, I think, to do something for them.

170
00:22:07,000 --> 00:22:15,000
So under the affairs of our department, we began to look at this issue.

171
00:22:15,000 --> 00:22:28,000
Secondly, the whole question of minimum wages and the areas that were left out of consideration for minimum wage status.

172
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:39,000
These areas were by large African-American workers, in contrast to the others who were workers from all down the southern hemisphere.

173
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:48,000
These were workers who would deny minimum wage covers, people who worked in private hospitals, nursing homes.

174
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:54,000
As we thought about this, this really required some involvement of the union if we were going to raise the issue.

175
00:22:54,000 --> 00:23:01,000
And we did, and we ultimately were victorious in getting coverage under the interstate commerce clause for these workers.

176
00:23:01,000 --> 00:23:08,000
Was there a minimum wage change in 1966 that extended agricultural workers?

177
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:18,000
I don't recall that, but I think it was about 66-67 under the interstate commerce clause that they extended it to private hospitals and nursing homes.

178
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:37,000
What I'm thinking of, and I'm not exactly sure of the date, but there was a period, I think, right after the Voting Rights Act passed, sort of in that time frame, where there was, I think, a dollar and an hour minimum wage for agricultural workers, which became the impetus for plantation owners and the delta to sort of finish mechanization and just completely run people.

179
00:23:37,000 --> 00:23:52,000
Off the plantations, which is part of what led to the poverty, the extreme hunger that led Marian Wright Edelman to propose the poor people's campaign with King.

180
00:23:52,000 --> 00:23:55,000
And so I was wondering if you were aware of the year.

181
00:23:55,000 --> 00:24:13,000
I'm just not aware of that, but it's clear that the minimum wage is both a blessing and a curse, I mean, because the employers simply take advantage of workers in certain categories.

182
00:24:13,000 --> 00:24:34,000
And there's a real need to see the minimum wage really as almost a floor for the improvement of the life of folks who either subscaled or unscaled, but doing medial work for which the employer decides the value.

183
00:24:34,000 --> 00:24:45,000
In your extensive work, do you have ideas for better ways to protect workers' rights and access to living wages and minimum wage?

184
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:55,000
I think collective bargaining is a simple, pure system, I mean, where workers have only their work to put into the game.

185
00:24:55,000 --> 00:25:06,000
The employers have to measure the value of that and you can't do it unless the two of them come together on the worker side, they have the right to withdraw their labor.

186
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:14,000
On the employer side, they have the decision to make about profit versus various fairness and generally they choose profit.

187
00:25:14,000 --> 00:25:24,000
And so absent a vehicle for workers to participate fully in the decision that affects them, you can always have exploitation.

188
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:36,000
When you came to Washington working for the Union full time, were there people who were important influences when you moved into that new job?

189
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:46,000
Yeah, the fellow who the president works in out to talk to me about his fellow by the Al Bilik.

190
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:59,000
And our unions are very, very, I mean, our union was not new, but our philosophy had changed substantially and we were making the case that public employees had the same rights as private sector employees.

191
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:23,000
I mean, there's fundamentally no difference in what many of us did and the fact that the civil service systems that said early had gone far beyond this mandate, we felt that we were entitled fully to if we if workers so chose to organize, to organize, be recognized and bargain the contract like it workers in the private sector.

192
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:42,000
And that was so very new and the proof of his newness was that public sector workers were to join us by the thousands because they never had or heard this kind of presentation to them as their rights.

193
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:54,000
And there were no, there were one or two states that allowed the process but not necessarily have the laws that protected workers in that process.

194
00:26:54,000 --> 00:27:11,000
There were many elected officials who saw the unfairness of the system who were prepared who actually bargain with public sector entities and proceeded to politically achieve the results of the process.

195
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:31,000
Of bargaining, I mean, the old argument was that the city, the county, the state is sort of a supreme power and the taxpayers, you know, pay the way well of the fact there's that they are sovereign entities but they're basically responsibilities provide public service.

196
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:37,000
And so they're employers at the same time.

197
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:42,000
So you end up being involved in the Memphis strike?

198
00:27:42,000 --> 00:27:47,000
Well, like a lot of people I got caught in the wrong place at the wrong time.

199
00:27:47,000 --> 00:28:01,000
I was, as I say, doing legislation and community affairs which is something that I was an alerting phase, this is 1968.

200
00:28:01,000 --> 00:28:08,000
I was, I ran into the president in the hallway one day and he says, what are you doing for the next couple of days?

201
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:11,000
I said, what I've been doing for the last couple of days.

202
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:16,000
So I'd like you to go to Detroit and do some work there.

203
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:24,000
And I agreed to do it and it called me back a little while later and says there's something going on in Memphis.

204
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:31,000
You're from Memphis, perhaps you could go down, take a look and see what it means.

205
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:38,000
The sanitation department in Memphis Tennessee was sort of in turmoil.

206
00:28:38,000 --> 00:28:50,000
You had men who had worked there to better part of their adult life and still earn in wages that allowed them to qualify for every poverty program that existed.

207
00:28:50,000 --> 00:28:55,000
As Dr. Martin Luther King Jr once said, it was really the true story of the working poor.

208
00:28:55,000 --> 00:29:08,000
Well, they were caught in a political squeeze between a brand new mayor who had got elected in a brand new system of governance.

209
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:19,000
And he won his election on probably some of the strongest racial things that had been seen for a long time.

210
00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:22,000
So he felt he owed to black community and nothing.

211
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:33,000
And he certainly in his new found power was not going to tolerate a union, talk about safety and health and wages and those kinds of things.

212
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:40,000
So a steelmate developed between a brand new mayor and a brand new system of city government.

213
00:29:40,000 --> 00:29:47,000
Prior to the strike start and there had been an attempt by these workers to influence the city.

214
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:51,000
They were enjoying by the local court from that.

215
00:29:51,000 --> 00:30:08,000
The catalyst to this new effort was men getting killed in the back of their garbage truck by the packing mechanism that scooped up the garbage and forced it into the back of the truck.

216
00:30:08,000 --> 00:30:13,000
This system had in the equipment had been complained about for some time.

217
00:30:13,000 --> 00:30:20,000
But the city, a new government, new mayor, old problems.

218
00:30:20,000 --> 00:30:25,000
They didn't see the need to address any of those problems at this time.

219
00:30:25,000 --> 00:30:33,000
This sort of festored for a while and then the catalyst, as I said, was the men being crushed in the back of the truck.

220
00:30:33,000 --> 00:30:37,000
The remaining workforce is that we just had enough of this.

221
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:44,000
Well, the last thing you need in a city like Memphis, Tennessee in February is a garbage strike.

222
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:54,000
I mean, strikes don't come because workers are mad. Strikes become because they're frustrated and have no ability to resolve the issues that contribute to the frustration.

223
00:30:55,000 --> 00:30:59,000
So they were preparing the strike to do something.

224
00:30:59,000 --> 00:31:06,000
I went from Detroit to Memphis just to get sort of a look at what was going on.

225
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:18,000
It was clear that this was a major issue that wasn't going to resolve itself in 24 hours because the city was entrenched in this position and the workers were in there.

226
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:24,000
And I sort of passed this on to the president and we thought about it for a minute.

227
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:30,000
We were subsequently notified by the Washington Posts.

228
00:31:30,000 --> 00:31:47,000
He fell off from the Washington Post. I can't recall his name now, but he was coming back oddly enough from a meeting in Marks, Mississippi that Dr. Martin Luther King Jr had been in as a part of his early movement towards the poor people's campaign.

229
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:52,000
And so they called us and said, it looks like there's a strike in Memphis, Tennessee.

230
00:31:52,000 --> 00:31:56,000
I mean, there's a strike in Memphis, Tennessee. He said, you ought to check it out.

231
00:31:56,000 --> 00:32:04,000
So we did again and this through the men had refused to, in the process of refusing to go to work.

232
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:08,000
And ultimately, they took that position.

233
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:12,000
And I was there to work with them myself.

234
00:32:12,000 --> 00:32:20,000
I fell about a name of Jesse Epps.

235
00:32:20,000 --> 00:32:28,000
Another fell about a name of Joe Paisley.

236
00:32:28,000 --> 00:32:39,000
And what we tried to do was just give some direction and some support to the workers until we figure out exactly what we're up against.

237
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:44,000
And the strike just got bigger and bigger.

238
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:57,000
It was a classic confrontation between a city with total power and a group of workers with no power other than a good idea.

239
00:32:57,000 --> 00:33:02,000
And the strike lasted for 67 days.

240
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:07,000
And clearly the story was Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.

241
00:33:07,000 --> 00:33:11,000
Ultimately, saw this as a great contradiction.

242
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:20,000
The rich nations and certainly rich cities yet to have people working for wages which will not allow them to bring themselves out of poverty.

243
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:28,000
And if you work every day, you ought to earn a wage sufficient to allow you to raise your family and so forth.

244
00:33:28,000 --> 00:33:39,000
During the course of the strike in the early days, Roy Wilkins by a restaurant.

245
00:33:39,000 --> 00:33:46,000
And ultimately, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr, this was a very quiet strike.

246
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:50,000
I mean, it was not well known outside of the city of Memphis.

247
00:33:50,000 --> 00:34:05,000
And we tried to ask people to come down and take a look, identify with it, who would bring some press with them because the Southern press don't give you a whole lot of play on worker activity.

248
00:34:05,000 --> 00:34:14,000
And then when Dr. Martin Luther King Jr came because he was traveling with the National Press, people had to have to see exactly what was taking place.

249
00:34:14,000 --> 00:34:24,000
And my hat and heart goes out to the men who participated in that because, I mean, whatever they had, it was on the line in that struggle.

250
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:32,000
How did having Dr. Martin Luther King Jr come in change the dynamics of the strike and what you were trying to do or able to do?

251
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:41,000
Well, we had spent a good deal of time trying to keep this as an imploreal, imploreal issue.

252
00:34:41,000 --> 00:34:57,000
And because we felt pretty strongly that if it became a question of a racial polarization that would be little sympathy for the men themselves because nobody knew anything about sanitation work.

253
00:34:57,000 --> 00:35:05,000
But it was impossible to do that. I mean, all of the elements suggested that you were going to ultimately wind up there.

254
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:12,000
What Dr. Martin Luther King Jr did was make this analogy that here is the problem in America.

255
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:20,000
You've got people who work every day but don't earn a sufficient enough wage to get themselves out of poverty.

256
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:32,000
We did an analysis of all the workers in that participation in 85-90% of them qualified for public aid, yet they worked every day.

257
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:47,000
And as we sort of talked to people, we really began to understand that people had no sense of the role that sanitation workers play in the social service system.

258
00:35:47,000 --> 00:35:59,000
And I think many of them thought they just put the garbage out and it disappeared overnight as opposed to somebody getting up at 4 o'clock in the morning and coming by, picking it up, putting it on that shoulder, taking it around, throwing it in the truck.

259
00:35:59,000 --> 00:36:02,000
So is this people in Memphis that you're talking to?

260
00:36:02,000 --> 00:36:05,000
I think that's where everyone's people generally cross countrymen.

261
00:36:05,000 --> 00:36:10,000
I mean, the last person you generally think about is somebody who picks up your garbage.

262
00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:20,000
I was on a radio show once out of New York and Westchester County, New York, which at that time was probably still pretty well to do.

263
00:36:20,000 --> 00:36:30,000
So a lady called in and just told them about making comments about you're paid for the value of what you do.

264
00:36:30,000 --> 00:36:34,000
I said, well, that's not quite true.

265
00:36:34,000 --> 00:36:38,000
She said, well, you know what I mean? I don't know what you're saying.

266
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:50,000
I mean, if you waited until about June or July, a garbage sanitation worker is somewhat more important than a lawyer in the context of the impact they have on public health.

267
00:36:50,000 --> 00:36:53,000
And so it was very quiet for a little while on the phone.

268
00:36:53,000 --> 00:36:55,000
And she said, well, thank you for your answer.

269
00:36:55,000 --> 00:37:05,000
Well, I thank you for your question because there's a lack of assessed value of public services.

270
00:37:05,000 --> 00:37:10,000
And the well to do, tend not to need public services.

271
00:37:10,000 --> 00:37:12,000
And so you have these contradictions.

272
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:21,000
If you get into a debate about a tax increase for sanitation work, you're probably not going to make it.

273
00:37:21,000 --> 00:37:31,000
So as opposed to if you want to build a sports arena.

274
00:37:31,000 --> 00:37:37,000
There was quite a bit of organizing throughout the Memphis community relation to the strike.

275
00:37:37,000 --> 00:37:42,000
We had to first get people to understand what was taking place.

276
00:37:42,000 --> 00:37:47,000
Because these men, as I said before, had never been seriously thought on.

277
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:57,000
What we asked them to do, because they touch every home in the city once or twice a week.

278
00:37:57,000 --> 00:38:01,000
And we asked them if they would do two things.

279
00:38:01,000 --> 00:38:08,000
If they have decided to make this confrontation, first of all, they need to go back home and talk to their wives.

280
00:38:08,000 --> 00:38:15,000
Because the last thing you need is home pressure if you're in the middle of a confrontation.

281
00:38:15,000 --> 00:38:25,000
And the second thing is to take a separate leak that leave it at the home of every home you touch in the course of your day's work.

282
00:38:25,000 --> 00:38:29,000
And explain to people what it is that's taking place.

283
00:38:29,000 --> 00:38:37,000
So at least the neutral at best and hopefully some would be supportive.

284
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:40,000
And that's what we got.

285
00:38:40,000 --> 00:38:46,000
We got pretty much solid support in the African American community.

286
00:38:46,000 --> 00:38:50,000
Because these are the people who live next door.

287
00:38:50,000 --> 00:39:01,000
We got a lukewarm support in the white community because they just had an election for a new form of government and new political leadership.

288
00:39:01,000 --> 00:39:10,000
And the belief was that the National had come down to take advantage of the city of Memphis.

289
00:39:10,000 --> 00:39:15,000
Some of this fostered by the FBI under J. Edgar Hoover.

290
00:39:15,000 --> 00:39:27,000
But for a union that's somewhat mature, the last thing you're going to have in the winter is a garbage strike in Memphis, Tennessee.

291
00:39:27,000 --> 00:39:39,000
And we were able, slowly but surely, to attract the religious community, at least to listen to the discussion and debate.

292
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:42,000
Ultimately, we wanted them to support us too.

293
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:53,000
But I mean, it took a while because the South, not just in the white community, but the Black community also, was not tuned into public sector trade unionism.

294
00:39:54,000 --> 00:39:59,000
I know that the slogan that you see on the sides, I am a man.

295
00:39:59,000 --> 00:40:07,000
And I know a historian who's written some interesting things about sort of what that means in terms of men and women.

296
00:40:07,000 --> 00:40:13,000
And that some people have really focused on this as something about manhood.

297
00:40:13,000 --> 00:40:20,000
And she says, you can look at pictures and see the huge numbers of women out on the streets protesting this.

298
00:40:20,000 --> 00:40:23,000
And she argues that it's a lot more complex than that.

299
00:40:23,000 --> 00:40:25,000
Oh, it is.

300
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:39,000
In spite of the wages, benefits, and lack of safety and all that kind of stuff, there were no tangible demands on the table that was the core of the strike.

301
00:40:39,000 --> 00:40:48,000
It was the lack of respect, the absence of dignity, that caused these workers to say, we just had enough.

302
00:40:48,000 --> 00:40:51,000
It was just really so hard to define.

303
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:54,000
I mean, if you talk to a reporter, he says, well, what's this about?

304
00:40:54,000 --> 00:40:57,000
You say respect and dignity. It's all right.

305
00:40:57,000 --> 00:41:01,000
There was just no understanding of it.

306
00:41:01,000 --> 00:41:07,000
And the men themselves, you know, you could listen to them talk.

307
00:41:07,000 --> 00:41:17,000
And you could see that for many of them, this is our first stand against a system that had virtually robbed them of any self-respect.

308
00:41:17,000 --> 00:41:21,000
Both as workers and even in their homes.

309
00:41:21,000 --> 00:41:27,000
You know, children who really didn't believe they were doing anything worthwhile.

310
00:41:27,000 --> 00:41:38,000
And so Rev. James M. Lawson Jr, who joined the strike early in the early days, had a press conference one day.

311
00:41:38,000 --> 00:41:41,000
And he was defining racism.

312
00:41:41,000 --> 00:41:52,000
And he says that racism in the context of what we were talking about was when a person treats a man like he's not a man.

313
00:41:52,000 --> 00:42:03,000
And we didn't think about that much at that point, but it became very clear that we had to have something that held this thing together.

314
00:42:03,000 --> 00:42:12,000
So one of the local ministers in myself was charged with going out, figuring out something.

315
00:42:12,000 --> 00:42:17,000
We said down on even that the Peabody Hotel there in Memphis, Tennessee.

316
00:42:17,000 --> 00:42:21,000
And we just started sort of playing with words and what had you.

317
00:42:21,000 --> 00:42:26,000
And what came to us was a statement that Rev. James M. Lawson Jr had made earlier.

318
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:29,000
And we tried to put this as simple as possible.

319
00:42:29,000 --> 00:42:34,000
And if you've seen one of the signs, they sort of blocked letters, you know, forwards.

320
00:42:34,000 --> 00:42:36,000
And it simply said, I am a man.

321
00:42:36,000 --> 00:42:46,000
And the impact of that on the workers, I mean, it defined for them all that they were about.

322
00:42:46,000 --> 00:42:51,000
Because these were like young workers. These were men who were middle age or older at that time.

323
00:42:51,000 --> 00:42:56,000
And I think they were replaying some of the disrespect they had heard.

324
00:42:56,000 --> 00:43:03,000
Because you don't understand, if you could go from boy to uncle to grandpa without ever stopping at men.

325
00:43:03,000 --> 00:43:09,000
And so they were so proud that this sign defined what they saw as their struggle.

326
00:43:09,000 --> 00:43:16,000
And can you talk about how you can have that slogan and my understanding is it doesn't exclude women.

327
00:43:16,000 --> 00:43:22,000
That there's still, you know, the women identify with this issue and not in the same way,

328
00:43:22,000 --> 00:43:26,000
but in a significant way that invites their participation.

329
00:43:26,000 --> 00:43:31,000
Well, I mean, if it had not been for the women, we'd still be on strike in Memphis.

330
00:43:31,000 --> 00:43:39,000
I mean, women-wise neighbors did so much to give their support to the effort.

331
00:43:39,000 --> 00:43:44,000
This was in no way a sort of a macho kind of thing.

332
00:43:44,000 --> 00:43:52,000
It was much more an emotional kind of thing and an expression of the frustrations that they had experienced over time.

333
00:43:52,000 --> 00:44:01,000
Not being able to play the simple role that a man would play in a family setting.

334
00:44:01,000 --> 00:44:06,000
It was just tremendous women support.

335
00:44:06,000 --> 00:44:09,000
And everybody had a role to play.

336
00:44:09,000 --> 00:44:15,000
Can you talk more about the different kinds of contributions, different people, different groups made?

337
00:44:15,000 --> 00:44:19,000
Well, by the time we got into a button, midway the strike.

338
00:44:19,000 --> 00:44:22,000
We had logistical needs like you wouldn't believe.

339
00:44:22,000 --> 00:44:24,000
We had feeding needs.

340
00:44:24,000 --> 00:44:28,000
We had all kind of economic needs.

341
00:44:28,000 --> 00:44:33,000
The church's role became sort of spiritual every day.

342
00:44:33,000 --> 00:44:39,000
We had to have an activity that gave people a chance to vent, you know.

343
00:44:39,000 --> 00:44:42,000
So the women would cook.

344
00:44:42,000 --> 00:44:45,000
The women would do the office work.

345
00:44:45,000 --> 00:44:47,000
The women would march on the picket lines.

346
00:44:47,000 --> 00:44:53,000
I mean, they did everything that they needed in order to make the strike successful.

347
00:44:53,000 --> 00:45:02,000
And it's, I mean, there's a tremendous story that needs to be told about the role that women played in the Memphis Sanitation Strike.

348
00:45:02,000 --> 00:45:04,000
And what about Reverend Lawson?

349
00:45:04,000 --> 00:45:06,000
You mentioned him a minute ago.

350
00:45:06,000 --> 00:45:13,000
Rev. James M. Lawson Jr was one of the unique individuals who had been a long time aid in ally of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.

351
00:45:13,000 --> 00:45:19,000
Rev. James M. Lawson Jr had studied, had studied Mohandas K. Gandhi tactics or studied under Mohandas K. Gandhi.

352
00:45:19,000 --> 00:45:22,000
I'm not sure which one maybe both.

353
00:45:22,000 --> 00:45:29,000
But it was a very strong spiritual leader in the Memphis community.

354
00:45:29,000 --> 00:45:33,000
And he identified with the strike very early.

355
00:45:33,000 --> 00:45:39,000
And so the earn the reputation of becoming the most hated African American in Memphis.

356
00:45:39,000 --> 00:45:43,000
Which was very, it was fine with Rev. James M. Lawson Jr.

357
00:45:43,000 --> 00:45:55,000
But he brought to the strike a sort of a new kind of vision in a very both emotional and intellectual context.

358
00:45:55,000 --> 00:46:02,000
And he helped to mobilize other ministers to come to the aid of the strike.

359
00:46:02,000 --> 00:46:12,000
You know, the story that the black church was right there instantly is sort of, you know, a little bit of a license for whoever writes it.

360
00:46:12,000 --> 00:46:19,000
Because the African American church had a little, if any experience with the Union's period.

361
00:46:19,000 --> 00:46:23,000
And public sector, the Union's probably none whatsoever.

362
00:46:23,000 --> 00:46:27,000
And so people did not want to be dragged into a fight that they didn't understand.

363
00:46:27,000 --> 00:46:31,000
And so it took some time for them to become very clear on what the issues were.

364
00:46:31,000 --> 00:46:35,000
And why the issues were having such impact on these men.

365
00:46:35,000 --> 00:46:39,000
I mean, many people thought they would go back to work the next day.

366
00:46:40,000 --> 00:46:43,000
But they didn't. They chose the strike.

367
00:46:43,000 --> 00:46:48,000
And no union can force people to strike.

368
00:46:48,000 --> 00:46:53,000
You know, work a strike out of frustration that their problems will not be dealt with.

369
00:46:53,000 --> 00:46:58,000
I'm sure there's, I know that there's a lot more I could ask you on Memphis.

370
00:46:58,000 --> 00:47:02,000
But I want to make sure we touch on a couple of other things as well.

371
00:47:02,000 --> 00:47:06,000
Let me just make this last point about Memphis.

372
00:47:07,000 --> 00:47:14,000
Dr. Martin Luther King Jr saw this, as I said, is the ultimate contradiction for people who work every day,

373
00:47:14,000 --> 00:47:17,000
but still cannot lift themselves out of poverty.

374
00:47:17,000 --> 00:47:25,000
So he aligned the Memphis strike with support people's campaign.

375
00:47:25,000 --> 00:47:29,000
And he was just totally committed to it.

376
00:47:29,000 --> 00:47:31,000
He came to Memphis twice.

377
00:47:32,000 --> 00:47:37,000
The first speech he gave, as we say, a barn burner.

378
00:47:37,000 --> 00:47:43,000
And his second preparation for the march, he was killed on April 4.

379
00:47:43,000 --> 00:47:49,000
Dr. Martin Luther King Jr gave what has now come to him, you know, is I've Been to the Mountaintop" speech,

380
00:47:49,000 --> 00:47:58,000
which was one of the better bringing together of the struggle of workers

381
00:47:58,000 --> 00:48:03,000
and contrasting with the richness of the country, the March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom, the struggles,

382
00:48:03,000 --> 00:48:10,000
because these men had fought for the country in the World War II.

383
00:48:10,000 --> 00:48:14,000
He just saw this as the great contradiction.

384
00:48:14,000 --> 00:48:23,000
And the tragedy is that the powers to be in Memphis did not listen to what he was suggesting,

385
00:48:23,000 --> 00:48:27,000
because his assassination did not have to take place.

386
00:48:27,000 --> 00:48:31,000
And I'm not one of those who have still convinced that James Earl Ray,

387
00:48:31,000 --> 00:48:35,000
as a lone person did this.

388
00:48:35,000 --> 00:48:40,000
I mean, you've got a burglar who gets from Memphis to Europe with no support.

389
00:48:40,000 --> 00:48:44,000
That's kind of a stretch.

390
00:48:44,000 --> 00:48:47,000
How did...

391
00:48:48,000 --> 00:48:52,000
I know that one of the things that people talk about in terms of Kane coming to Memphis

392
00:48:52,000 --> 00:48:56,000
and the two visits is the issue of nonviolence.

393
00:48:56,000 --> 00:48:59,000
And so maybe we could speak to that.

394
00:48:59,000 --> 00:49:08,000
Well, there were young folks at Memphis who thought that tactics were less sufficient.

395
00:49:08,000 --> 00:49:16,000
And they were anxious to get engaged in the strike support effort.

396
00:49:16,000 --> 00:49:21,000
There was a group there called the The Invaders, The Invaders,

397
00:49:21,000 --> 00:49:27,000
a whole bunch of young kids who were community-minded and certainly committed to the benefit of the community,

398
00:49:27,000 --> 00:49:31,000
but promoting violence, that wasn't them.

399
00:49:31,000 --> 00:49:38,000
As a record shows, and certainly Senate Select Committee on Intelligence Activities a year or so later,

400
00:49:38,000 --> 00:49:43,000
I showed that many of those who participated in the violence were provocateurs.

401
00:49:44,000 --> 00:49:49,000
Some from the FBI service, and I guess some from other places,

402
00:49:49,000 --> 00:49:58,000
but on the day of the last King March, the window breaking in all of the violence and damage,

403
00:49:58,000 --> 00:50:00,000
this was a compilation of things.

404
00:50:00,000 --> 00:50:05,000
And it was not young people by themselves. It was provocateurs.

405
00:50:06,000 --> 00:50:14,000
And the sad part, it has never been a full review of that participation.

406
00:50:14,000 --> 00:50:15,000
Yeah.

407
00:50:15,000 --> 00:50:24,000
And I think the effort was to ruin King's image as not being able to, at that point in time,

408
00:50:24,000 --> 00:50:30,000
hold a nonviolent assembly, whether it be a march or a rally.

409
00:50:30,000 --> 00:50:39,000
I know that there was concern for King and others in SCLC about what the implications of this would be for the poor people's campaign,

410
00:50:39,000 --> 00:50:41,000
bringing so many people to Washington.

411
00:50:41,000 --> 00:50:52,000
Well, I think that was, I think, the thrust, and probably the alleged pain that made some folks decide to help the violence.

412
00:50:53,000 --> 00:50:57,000
I mean, trade unions will discipline people.

413
00:50:57,000 --> 00:51:02,000
I mean, the violence is not an asset.

414
00:51:02,000 --> 00:51:12,000
And what they used it for on that day was to polarize the city, the county, and the state.

415
00:51:12,000 --> 00:51:17,000
And they succeeded in doing just that because it's right.

416
00:51:18,000 --> 00:51:21,000
We think would have been shortened, absent the violence.

417
00:51:21,000 --> 00:51:27,000
The mayor brought in the National Guard and a whole new set of dynamics were put into play.

418
00:51:27,000 --> 00:51:31,000
What were your interactions with Dr. Martin Luther King Jr in that context?

419
00:51:31,000 --> 00:51:41,000
I made with him only once at the Rivermont Hotel at the end of the march that was broken up that day.

420
00:51:41,000 --> 00:51:43,000
I forget the date.

421
00:51:43,000 --> 00:51:47,000
And it was just an analysis of what took place.

422
00:51:47,000 --> 00:51:51,000
I was in meetings where he was present with a lot of other folks with that day.

423
00:51:51,000 --> 00:51:55,000
He said that he talked about the down side of what had happened.

424
00:51:55,000 --> 00:51:58,000
What was that like, that meeting like?

425
00:51:58,000 --> 00:52:02,000
It had been a pretty exciting day.

426
00:52:03,000 --> 00:52:06,000
And we were trying to assess it.

427
00:52:06,000 --> 00:52:11,000
We were trying to figure out what do we do next?

428
00:52:11,000 --> 00:52:16,000
And of real concern, what are we exposing these men to?

429
00:52:16,000 --> 00:52:20,000
What are we allowing them to expose themselves to?

430
00:52:20,000 --> 00:52:24,000
And the word was, it has to be another march.

431
00:52:24,000 --> 00:52:31,000
So what kind of impact did his assassination have on the, from your perspective, the Memphis strike?

432
00:52:31,000 --> 00:52:34,000
And maybe you personally?

433
00:52:34,000 --> 00:52:40,000
Well, let me do the last one for that incredible life-old and experienced only personally.

434
00:52:40,000 --> 00:52:45,000
Because you know, it's just unbelievable that something like this could happen.

435
00:52:45,000 --> 00:52:49,000
Totally unnecessary.

436
00:52:49,000 --> 00:52:55,000
But in the context of the strike tactics,

437
00:52:56,000 --> 00:53:09,000
we heard one reporter from a local paper wrote an article that said he was just so sorry that Dr. Martin Luther King Jr had been killed in Memphis,

438
00:53:09,000 --> 00:53:14,000
with emphasis on in Memphis.

439
00:53:15,000 --> 00:53:24,000
So for us who were staff, I mean, our commitment was pushed to the hill.

440
00:53:24,000 --> 00:53:28,000
I mean, we had to do something with this thing.

441
00:53:28,000 --> 00:53:33,000
But we at first had to resolve the question of street violence.

442
00:53:33,000 --> 00:53:39,000
Not so much by strikers, by other people who were just so frustrated over the assassination of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.

443
00:53:39,000 --> 00:53:43,000
And then you had a whole lot of whackles from other places.

444
00:53:43,000 --> 00:53:47,000
You know, Arkansas, Mississippi, et cetera.

445
00:53:47,000 --> 00:53:52,000
Who saw this as an opportunity to act out some of their peanut up hostility.

446
00:53:52,000 --> 00:53:59,000
So we in Memphis had to get a system of safety for strikers.

447
00:53:59,000 --> 00:54:08,000
We had to sort of help the church and other parts of the community.

448
00:54:08,000 --> 00:54:14,000
Provide a sense of protection for people who were going to be exposed as the police were.

449
00:54:14,000 --> 00:54:17,000
We're just openly hostile.

450
00:54:17,000 --> 00:54:20,000
So we had to work on that.

451
00:54:20,000 --> 00:54:25,000
And at the same time, we have to decide what the men wanted to do.

452
00:54:25,000 --> 00:54:37,000
And they were ready to go back as they say downtown because the marches were from Clayborn Temple AME Church to City Hall.

453
00:54:37,000 --> 00:54:49,000
So after the memorial service, you know, which was held, I guess a week or so later, a couple of weeks later after this funeral service in Atlanta, we got back to strike tactics.

454
00:54:49,000 --> 00:55:06,000
President Lyndon B. Johnson gave us a tremendous amount of, have I shouldn't say, gave us, but in an effort to resolve the issue assigned James J. Reynolds.

455
00:55:06,000 --> 00:55:20,000
As a mediator in this process, and Mr. Reynolds searched out and found a fellow by the name of Frank Miles to work with.

456
00:55:20,000 --> 00:55:28,000
Because even the mayor just refused and negotiate, refused to discuss, you'll post it for the cameras, et cetera.

457
00:55:28,000 --> 00:55:32,000
And it was really time to resolve this.

458
00:55:33,000 --> 00:55:38,000
In contrast, in the fact, we had resolved this strike twice before.

459
00:55:38,000 --> 00:55:46,000
So I mean, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr's passing on, sure, put some pressure into that situation.

460
00:55:46,000 --> 00:55:51,000
I know you said initially you were trying very hard to keep it as a labor issue.

461
00:55:51,000 --> 00:55:56,000
But clearly with King's involvement, it becomes very identified with civil rights.

462
00:55:56,000 --> 00:55:59,000
Well, it became that before King came.

463
00:55:59,000 --> 00:56:03,000
There were civil rights activists in town.

464
00:56:03,000 --> 00:56:09,000
They were not, they said, who knew the thing about the union, but they just saw men on strike.

465
00:56:09,000 --> 00:56:16,000
In fact, at 99.9% of more African Americans, you know, sort of say what it said.

466
00:56:16,000 --> 00:56:25,000
So how did that, I mean, did you, in the end, did you think that was a good thing, or did it change your thinking on that at all?

467
00:56:26,000 --> 00:56:36,000
I think for a while, I thought we ultimately thought we should have identified it as a racial issue from the start.

468
00:56:36,000 --> 00:56:43,000
And our hope was that rational thinking, white Memphis, which see this for what it was.

469
00:56:43,000 --> 00:56:49,000
It was a labor dispute in the conditions, I mean, it could be reviewed by anybody.

470
00:56:49,000 --> 00:57:07,000
What did happen, we found a way to take some well to do white women, to visit the homes of not so well to do African American women husbands of sanitation workers.

471
00:57:07,000 --> 00:57:14,000
And they obviously couldn't believe what they were seeing.

472
00:57:14,000 --> 00:57:25,000
And we had hoped that they would become a voice of both moderation and observation in this process.

473
00:57:25,000 --> 00:57:38,000
And there was, there was enough pressure generated to get the mayor to participate in some forums, Q&A kind of stuff.

474
00:57:38,000 --> 00:57:49,000
And when people heard the conditions on which the mayor worked, the other factors, you could see people's mind changes for a long part of the strike.

475
00:57:49,000 --> 00:57:59,000
People just blindly committed to the positions that Mayor Henry Loeb III took without any discussion of whether or not they were accurate enough.

476
00:57:59,000 --> 00:58:05,000
You mentioned just a few minutes ago that the strike had been resolved twice before. Can you talk about?

477
00:58:05,000 --> 00:58:08,000
We are.

478
00:58:08,000 --> 00:58:22,000
In the early days, one or two days after the strike started, several of the staff, people including myself, was in the mayor's office talking to the mayor trying to explain to him what was going on.

479
00:58:22,000 --> 00:58:31,000
And it was a very simple process at that point. The men says they want to have the union speak for them.

480
00:58:31,000 --> 00:58:37,000
And they want to talk about safety and health because you just had these men get killed in this.

481
00:58:37,000 --> 00:58:46,000
And the mayor took the position that this is an illegal strike. And he would not talk to people who were breaking the law.

482
00:58:46,000 --> 00:58:52,000
You know, which was about as backwards thinking as you could find. So we said, look, this is not complicated.

483
00:58:52,000 --> 00:59:05,000
Let us sit down and talk about what we're trying to, trying to solve. And so he allowed one of his fellow fellow by the name of Janati, which was one of the city attorneys.

484
00:59:05,000 --> 00:59:12,000
The Janati and a couple of us went into a side room and just started working on what do you think will take to get this resolved.

485
00:59:12,000 --> 00:59:18,000
And so we came up with what we call a recognition clause, etc.

486
00:59:18,000 --> 00:59:28,000
We agree with the committee agreed with it. And since Mr. Janati represented the mayor, we assume that he certainly wouldn't agree to anything, but the mayor didn't agree to it.

487
00:59:28,000 --> 00:59:37,000
So we took it back to show him this one paragraph of paragraph and a half deal. And the mayor went bananas.

488
00:59:37,000 --> 00:59:47,000
And so we kept saying, well, the hardest thing to do is to try and work with somebody who don't know what they're doing.

489
00:59:47,000 --> 00:59:55,000
And so it was clear to us that they just had to hands full and have no background on what's taking place.

490
00:59:55,000 --> 01:00:06,000
The second time, spring from a meeting that we had, which involves a mayor. And President Wurf was there.

491
01:00:06,000 --> 01:00:16,000
We talked about the issues and each day the strike goes on, you get some new issues. Because the people are going through a little bit more pain.

492
01:00:16,000 --> 01:00:22,000
So we finally found something that we thought everybody could agree on. It didn't involve money. None of that.

493
01:00:22,000 --> 01:00:32,000
And the mayor said he thought he could live with that. Well, somebody from the mayor's side called the press, followed the meeting, and gave him a story.

494
01:00:32,000 --> 01:00:38,000
And the next morning's headlines was Mayor Capitulates".

495
01:00:38,000 --> 01:00:50,000
And you know, everything just unraveled. And he was taking polls in the white community. How many was for him? How many was against him?

496
01:00:50,000 --> 01:00:55,000
And as long as he had his pro support out there in big numbers, he figured, why does he have to worry?

497
01:00:55,000 --> 01:01:06,000
So he just walked backwards from the agreement we had reached. And ultimately, he never did come back into the discussions.

498
01:01:06,000 --> 01:01:19,000
He put some city council people. Well, there was just one point to be make. There was a fellow there who, not necessarily pro-U. But he was pro-Fair.

499
01:01:19,000 --> 01:01:31,000
And he, I worked with a number of the council members and had got enough. He was one vote short of getting the city council to get engaged and involved in a fine solution to this thing.

500
01:01:31,000 --> 01:01:50,000
And his name was Lewis Donelson. I spoke to him years later and he said that he was just so dismayed. And it really took the burden himself with Dr. Martin Luther King Jr's assassination, because he just said he could never have, he did not find the one more vote that he thought he needed.

501
01:01:50,000 --> 01:01:59,000
And that if he had been able to be more convincing, perhaps he would never would have happened. I'm not sure I agree with that, but that was his story.

502
01:01:59,000 --> 01:02:19,000
In, after the assassination, we found ways and means of putting the language together to form an agreement. And the mayor stood back from it and allowed it to move forward through the city council. And by then it was about money.

503
01:02:19,000 --> 01:02:42,000
And the mayor never put any money into the settlement. But one of the fairly wealthy industrialists there in Memphis fell about the name of Abe Plough, who owned Abe Plough, put up enough money to satisfy the demands that were on the table. And we then moved the contract towards ratification.

504
01:02:42,000 --> 01:02:49,000
From what you were just saying and what I've read, it seems like Mayor (Henry) Loeb was a big stumbling block.

505
01:02:49,000 --> 01:03:06,000
Well, he was it. I mean, there was no, I mean, the city council, the city council once recommended a resolution. And apparently they were jackhammered into back and away from that.

506
01:03:06,000 --> 01:03:18,000
But Mayor (Henry) Loeb never engaged in it. He said, it was an illegal strike. And he wasn't going to break the law, which is a strange outlook for a major employer.

507
01:03:18,000 --> 01:03:28,000
But in the end, the city council ratified the agreement. The workers ratified the agreement. And Loeb just went his merry way.

508
01:03:28,000 --> 01:03:43,000
And the irony is that Loeb became a protester himself. I mean, he was a big agricultural issue in 69 or 70. I forget when the tractors all came to town.

509
01:03:43,000 --> 01:03:53,000
He was watching the DC and circled the capital and did all this. Well, he was a leader in the tractor protest movement.

510
01:03:54,000 --> 01:04:07,000
So do you take credit for teaching and protest? I kind of think that at some point in time he regretted having painted himself into a corner early in the strike.

511
01:04:07,000 --> 01:04:14,000
He certainly did. And it became a question of face saving, even to do the right thing.

512
01:04:14,000 --> 01:04:25,000
So Mr. Lucy, I know you said you had a meeting to go to and it's right about 12. Can I ask you just a couple of big questions about the rest of some of the other highlights.

513
01:04:25,000 --> 01:04:30,000
I don't even know if that would be the right. And then you can pick and choose and answer what you.

514
01:04:30,000 --> 01:04:41,000
So I know that you were instrumental or crucial in organizing the coalition of black trade unionists and also the free South Africa movement.

515
01:04:41,000 --> 01:04:51,000
And of course, we're approaching the 50th anniversary of the March on Washington for jobs and freedom. And I know sometimes people miss that jobs part of the jobs and freedom and economic issues.

516
01:04:51,000 --> 01:05:06,000
And sort of related to this to sort of the significance, I guess. Well, I'm thinking in terms of the coalition of black trade unionists sort of asked me, I understand, was a pretty white union when you joined it nationally. I don't know if that's right.

517
01:05:06,000 --> 01:05:12,000
Actually, when we joined it, the percentage of people of color was higher, but the union was smaller.

518
01:05:12,000 --> 01:05:25,000
Okay. Coalition of Black Trade Unionists came about really as a protest and reaction to the AFL CIOs.

519
01:05:25,000 --> 01:05:33,000
Almost refusal to get engaged in the battle between George McGovern and Richard Nixon.

520
01:05:33,000 --> 01:05:37,000
And I believe that I forget what year that election was, but 72.

521
01:05:37,000 --> 01:05:57,000
72, I mean, you know, the endorsement process is critically important. And we had watched Richard Nixon for four years with his price controls and wage controls and his just over disdain for the African American and poor community.

522
01:05:57,000 --> 01:06:06,000
So at the convention of the AFL-CIO prior to the Democratic National Convention, the AFL-CIO, we're taking a position of neutrality.

523
01:06:06,000 --> 01:06:12,000
Which in our community suggests that one's no different than the other or one's no better than the other.

524
01:06:12,000 --> 01:06:18,000
And we got Richard Nixon with a dreadful record with regards to working people, poor people, black people.

525
01:06:18,000 --> 01:06:28,000
As opposed to McGovern, who had a progressive record, both in his participation in Congress and in the Senate, I should say.

526
01:06:28,000 --> 01:06:41,000
Otherwise, so our view was clearly your decision to remain neutral does not take into consideration the impact that one candidate has had on our broad community.

527
01:06:41,000 --> 01:07:03,000
And we believe that there was a real need for our voice to be in that process. And not that the AFL-CIO was wrong or bad, it just simply had not considered in the context of our interest what Nixon was and had done and would do.

528
01:07:03,000 --> 01:07:09,000
And so some of us decided that we had to figure out how to make sure our voice was in the room.

529
01:07:09,000 --> 01:07:25,000
So about four or five of the colleagues, Nelson Jack Edwards, Charles A. Hayes from what is now the United Food and Commercial Workers, which at that time was retail clerks, something like that.

530
01:07:25,000 --> 01:07:31,000
Cleveland Robinson.

531
01:07:31,000 --> 01:07:37,000
Well, that's one of William H. "Bill" Simons from the American Federation of Teachers.

532
01:07:37,000 --> 01:07:50,000
We concluded that we already have a meeting just talk about what had just happened and to see how we can sort of influences process in years to come.

533
01:07:51,000 --> 01:07:57,000
And we thought that rather than ourselves having all the wisdom, we all asked some other people.

534
01:07:57,000 --> 01:08:07,000
So we set a meeting for Chicago and just sort of talked to people and said, here's what we're thinking about doing.

535
01:08:07,000 --> 01:08:11,000
You want to be a part of this conversation, come to Chicago.

536
01:08:11,000 --> 01:08:18,000
We didn't have a mailing list, a tweeter's a Twitter or email and that stuff, it's just word of mouth.

537
01:08:19,000 --> 01:08:25,000
At this meeting, 1,300 trade union to show that.

538
01:08:25,000 --> 01:08:29,000
And the surprise, we didn't even know there was that many out there.

539
01:08:29,000 --> 01:08:34,000
But obviously it was an idea that lots of other people had thought about.

540
01:08:34,000 --> 01:08:36,000
Some of them had actually done.

541
01:08:36,000 --> 01:08:44,000
Mr. Randolph, a A. Philip Randolph, it had the Negro American Labor Council, I think it was legal.

542
01:08:45,000 --> 01:08:48,000
And they had worked for a number of years.

543
01:08:48,000 --> 01:08:51,000
Some of these same kinds of issues.

544
01:08:51,000 --> 01:08:56,000
But there was never, it was not as serious then as it was in 1972.

545
01:08:56,000 --> 01:09:03,000
So when we had the convention, we did not say we have formed Coalition of Black Trade Unionists.

546
01:09:03,000 --> 01:09:08,000
And he said, we ought to take about a year and talk about this.

547
01:09:08,000 --> 01:09:11,000
And we've got to be talked about in all parts of the country.

548
01:09:11,000 --> 01:09:20,000
So lots of people were given assignments to go here, go there, meet with workers, meet with labor leadership, black leadership,

549
01:09:20,000 --> 01:09:24,000
and raise the question, is this a time for such a zest?

550
01:09:24,000 --> 01:09:30,000
And it was not set out to be a coalition of black trade unionists.

551
01:09:30,000 --> 01:09:33,000
At the end of the day, we came back into a second convention.

552
01:09:33,000 --> 01:09:37,000
And the answer in response to the question was yes.

553
01:09:37,000 --> 01:09:43,000
We need an organization such as this to make sure our voices don't get lost.

554
01:09:43,000 --> 01:09:49,000
And we intentionally called it Coalition of Black Trade Unionists.

555
01:09:49,000 --> 01:09:53,000
I mean, with Malice of Fourth, I should say.

556
01:09:53,000 --> 01:09:58,000
And the idea was to get people, I mean there's nothing wrong with diversity.

557
01:09:58,000 --> 01:10:03,000
There's nothing wrong with people getting together to discuss mutual concerns.

558
01:10:03,000 --> 01:10:07,000
But we said we've got to be very clear that issues we're going to deal with.

559
01:10:07,000 --> 01:10:10,000
We're going to come back from a black perspective.

560
01:10:10,000 --> 01:10:15,000
And everybody, I mean it's open to membership for everybody, but that's the focal point.

561
01:10:15,000 --> 01:10:19,000
And the convention voted to name it that.

562
01:10:19,000 --> 01:10:27,000
And we've grown to some 55 chapters now.

563
01:10:27,000 --> 01:10:32,000
Some just dynamite coalitions of workers, some label only.

564
01:10:32,000 --> 01:10:40,000
But it has brought to consciousness the focus that there are unique problems that women have in the workforce,

565
01:10:40,000 --> 01:10:43,000
Hispanics have in the workforce, African-American.

566
01:10:43,000 --> 01:10:49,000
And you can't sort of use a philosophy of 1948.

567
01:10:49,000 --> 01:10:51,000
I mean, it's a little bit different now.

568
01:10:51,000 --> 01:10:57,000
And do you think you've been able to have an impact through that on the sort of approach of the broader labor movement?

569
01:10:57,000 --> 01:10:58,000
Well, I think so.

570
01:10:58,000 --> 01:11:04,000
I mean, our initial argument was that we're not in the room with these decisions of the executive council

571
01:11:04,000 --> 01:11:07,000
in those days were substantially smaller.

572
01:11:07,000 --> 01:11:14,000
Now, I mean in 1955, we increased the council by 12 persons,

573
01:11:14,000 --> 01:11:18,000
aside from those who may have gotten elected on their own.

574
01:11:18,000 --> 01:11:26,000
But now it's a diverse policy-making body with women, with Hispanics, with Asians, with African-Americans.

575
01:11:26,000 --> 01:11:34,000
So when you take on domestic economic policy, when you take on foreign policy,

576
01:11:34,000 --> 01:11:41,000
I mean, you're speaking with the folks who are experiencing the impact of it on a daily basis.

577
01:11:41,000 --> 01:11:47,000
With many whole high levels of leadership in their own individual organizations.

578
01:11:47,000 --> 01:11:52,000
In those days, Mr. Randolph, I think, was probably the only African-American on the council,

579
01:11:52,000 --> 01:11:55,000
perhaps C.L. Dellums and C.L. Dellums.

580
01:11:55,000 --> 01:12:06,000
But the fact is that people have educated themselves as the role and value of trade unions.

581
01:12:06,000 --> 01:12:12,000
And they are full participants, and we call ourselves full partners.

582
01:12:12,000 --> 01:12:20,000
And we've lasted 43 years, a little bit longer than a lot of others.

583
01:12:20,000 --> 01:12:24,000
But I think, you know, we're still going at it.

584
01:12:24,000 --> 01:12:26,000
We're going to move Nelson Mandela.

585
01:12:26,000 --> 01:12:30,000
Let me just spend a moment on that.

586
01:12:30,000 --> 01:12:39,000
We have long since we've been coalition-black trade unions believe that apartheid was an abomination that should not exist.

587
01:12:39,000 --> 01:12:48,000
And we have long held that there ought to be free and fair elections, not just in South Africa, but across the undeveloped world.

588
01:12:48,000 --> 01:12:53,000
I mean, people ought to have an opportunity to participate in the decision that's who will lead them.

589
01:12:53,000 --> 01:13:02,000
And apartheid was a special brand of evil that a lot of people made excuses for.

590
01:13:02,000 --> 01:13:05,000
And it was go-alonged alone.

591
01:13:05,000 --> 01:13:22,000
In 1984, I believe it was, we just started to look at this and how can a free labor movement really work side by side with something like apartheid.

592
01:13:22,000 --> 01:13:28,000
Again, the American labor movement did not step up to the challenge in front of it.

593
01:13:28,000 --> 01:13:37,000
So we took on the battle of sensitizing the country to the evils of apartheid, President Reagan, I believe, was an office at that time.

594
01:13:37,000 --> 01:13:51,000
And we were set out with a specific goal to undo it, or disengage US policy from Africa in general, well, South Africa specifically.

595
01:13:51,000 --> 01:13:59,000
Under the leadership of Randall Robinson, we have formed what is called TransAfrica.

596
01:13:59,000 --> 01:14:07,000
And it was specifically a body to put black thought into foreign policy.

597
01:14:07,000 --> 01:14:17,000
And in 1984, we took on the role of trying to form something that will spread this discussion in debate nationwide.

598
01:14:17,000 --> 01:14:22,000
So we formed a free South Africa movement out of a number of other movements.

599
01:14:22,000 --> 01:14:25,000
And it took a while, but we finally got there.

600
01:14:25,000 --> 01:14:34,000
Nelson Mandela was ultimately released from prison, ultimately became president of South Africa.

601
01:14:34,000 --> 01:14:39,000
And now is gravely ill.

602
01:14:39,000 --> 01:14:54,000
But we have seen Africa in general and South Africa particularly move from colonial domination to independent democracies in many cases.

603
01:14:54,000 --> 01:14:59,000
Why did you think it was important to bring Nelson Mandela here?

604
01:14:59,000 --> 01:15:15,000
I think on his tour of 1990, and had two purposes, one to give him an opportunity to define and project what he sees for South Africa, what he saw for South Africa in terms of a non-racial society.

605
01:15:15,000 --> 01:15:25,000
And second, let the country see someone who had spent 27 years in prison for expressing that thought in South Africa.

606
01:15:25,000 --> 01:15:35,000
It was such an incredible impact on the country as a whole.

607
01:15:35,000 --> 01:15:40,000
I think a lot of minds were changed. A lot of people were educated.

608
01:15:40,000 --> 01:15:46,000
A lot of people became much more knowledgeable about the fact that there ought to be engagement in foreign policy.

609
01:15:46,000 --> 01:15:56,000
We've been alive in South Africa since the apartheid inception and never complained about it once.

610
01:15:56,000 --> 01:16:02,000
And whether it was regular, any others who proceeded, Republicans and Democrats alike.

611
01:16:02,000 --> 01:16:08,000
And we found a rationale for continuing to relate to an evil system.

612
01:16:08,000 --> 01:16:14,000
Could I ask a little bit about, do you think it's irrelevant? You don't have to answer.

613
01:16:14,000 --> 01:16:20,000
After the apartheid was abolished in South Africa, there was a security of truth and reconciliation.

614
01:16:20,000 --> 01:16:27,000
Do you think America needs such an acknowledgement of...

615
01:16:27,000 --> 01:16:42,000
Well, I don't think there's any question that's a lot of issues that could be put before a truth commission to have folks either admit to that participation in it, argue for its larger existence.

616
01:16:42,000 --> 01:16:56,000
I mean, if they can make that argument, I mean, you've got to have ongoing tragedies that grow out of our history and our systems across the South.

617
01:16:56,000 --> 01:17:03,000
So we profess the need for democracy around the world, yet we sequirely buy while folks are denied the right to vote.

618
01:17:03,000 --> 01:17:10,000
Or we rationalize the reason why they shouldn't vote.

619
01:17:10,000 --> 01:17:19,000
As opposed to South Africa, who... or Brazil is mandatory that you vote.

620
01:17:19,000 --> 01:17:25,000
I mean, I think if we want to really test our system, let's make voting mandatory.

621
01:17:25,000 --> 01:17:35,000
And you would see the divisions that exist in the country with regards to who should participate in democracy.

622
01:17:35,000 --> 01:17:47,000
And I think some of the past ills and racism that exists, not just in the South, but in the North as well, are let's say across the country.

623
01:17:47,000 --> 01:17:52,000
I could really bear some airing out.

624
01:17:52,000 --> 01:18:01,000
I think half people simply share their views. I mean, it really goes back to what he'd be the voice that the problem of our country is race.

625
01:18:01,000 --> 01:18:07,000
I mean, we're debating now the comprehensive immigration reform.

626
01:18:07,000 --> 01:18:20,000
I mean, who was here first? Everybody is immigrant of some type. And we're still debating those kinds of questions.

627
01:18:20,000 --> 01:18:31,000
Mr. Lucia, I want to respect your time. So I know we all have many more questions, but thank you very much for being with us today. I appreciate it.

628
01:18:31,000 --> 01:18:34,000
I really want to take a closer look.

629
01:18:34,000 --> 01:18:43,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

